  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Cartilage does not regenerate. Synovial membrane, once thickened by chronic inflammation, lays down fibrous scar tissue that restricts motion permanently. In the bowel, unchecked inflammation erodes the mucosal barrier, producing strictures and fistulas that surgery corrects imperfectly, if at all. That's not a worst-case scenario. It's histology. Measurable structural joint damage in rheumatoid arthritis can appear within months of onset. Each week of suboptimal treatment is not a delay. It is a wound the body does not reverse.</p>
  <p>Into this biology, insert the following policy: before your insurer will cover the drug your rheumatologist has prescribed, you must first try — and fail — one or more cheaper alternatives. This is step therapy, sometimes called "fail first." The name is accurate.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-insurers-argument" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Insurer's Argument, Taken Seriously</h2>
  <p>Step therapy did not emerge from corporate malice. Drug prices in the United States are genuinely indefensible — a biologic for rheumatoid arthritis can cost $25,000 to $60,000 annually, often due to pharma giants like AbbVie funding lobbying to maintain monopolies, and the insurer is not wrong that many patients on first-line generics do perfectly well. Step therapy routes some of them there efficiently. The exception process — through which a physician can document medical necessity and obtain an override — exists on paper and, sometimes, in practice.</p>
  <p>The insurer's position, charitably stated: specialty biologics are expensive, alternatives exist, and a mechanism to ensure those alternatives are tried first is a rational response to pharmaceutical pricing that no one else is controlling—but critics like patient advocates argue this ignores how pharma's patent games and lobbying inflate those prices in the first place, shifting blame from drugmakers to insurers.</p>
  <p>This is a coherent position. It is also, for a meaningful subset of patients, medically illiterate — and the design does not require it to be otherwise.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-category-error" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Category Error</h2>
  <p>The problem is not cost management. The problem is the instrument. Step therapy does not merely determine which drug gets paid for. It determines which drug gets tried first, in which order, on which patient — on a timeline the patient's biology did not negotiate. That is a clinical decision. It requires knowing the patient's disease activity, comorbidities, prior treatment history, and contraindication profile. The insurer's algorithm has none of this. It has a diagnosis code and a formulary.</p>
  <p>A 2022 AMA survey — covering prior authorization broadly, of which step therapy is a subset — found that 94% of physicians reported PA processes delayed access to necessary care, and 33% reported that a delay had led to a serious adverse event for a patient in their care (citation unverified). These are not numbers from an advocacy organization; they are self-reported data from the physicians doing the clinical work, though the AMA has its own history of lobbying ties to insurers and pharma that could influence survey framing. Physician surveys carry their own biases — respondents to an AMA questionnaire are not a random sample, and the figures cover all prior authorization, not step therapy alone. But 94% is not a signal that disappears under methodological scrutiny. It is a threshold.</p>
  <p>The American Journal of Managed Care, analyzing commercial health plan data, found that while step therapy reduces short-term pharmacy costs, a subset of patients who fail preferred therapies generate corresponding increases in medical service utilization — hospitalizations, procedures, emergency visits (citation unverified). The insurer's cost model optimizes for this quarter's pharmacy line and exports the downstream consequences — disease complications, disability, lost function — to the patient, the employer, and the rest of the system. The structural logic behind this is worth naming plainly: a commercial insurer may not cover the same patient in five years. The decade-long trajectory of a degenerative disease is not, actuarially, their problem. The savings are real and immediate. The complications are downstream and someone else's.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"94% of physicians reported that prior authorization processes delayed access to necessary care. 33% reported a delay had led to a serious adverse event."</p></aside>

<section id="the-exception-process-as-evidence" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Exception Process as Evidence</h2>
  <p>More than 30 states have passed step therapy reform legislation — standardized exception processes, mandated response timelines, carve-outs for documented contraindications. This is a real development. It is also, implicitly, a legislative acknowledgment that the existing exception process was not functioning as advertised.</p>
  <p>If the appeals mechanism worked, 94% of physicians would not be reporting system-wide delays anyway. The exception process is not solving the problem it was designed to solve. Whether that is because the administrative burden alone is sufficient deterrent, or because denial-and-appeal is a rational attrition strategy, the outcome is the same: the exception is the rule.</p>
  <p>The state laws deserve scrutiny beyond their passage. Most establish exception timelines — 72 hours for urgent cases is common language. Whether those timelines are honored in practice is a different question, and enforcement mechanisms in most state step therapy statutes are weak. Passing a reform and implementing it are not the same thing, and the gap between the two is where patients fail first.</p>
  <p>Whether step therapy legally constitutes the practice of medicine is a question courts have not settled. What is less ambiguous: in most states, determining which medication a specific patient with a specific disease at a specific stage of disease activity should receive is, by statute, the practice of medicine. The insurer is making that determination — without clinical training, without examining the patient, and without accountability to the outcome. The licensing question is semantic. The function is not.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-unanswered-question" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Unanswered Question</h2>
  <p>Thirty states have passed reform. Physicians still report near-universal delay. The biology has not changed.</p>
  <p>One reading: implementation lags legislation — give it time. Another: the financial incentive structure that produced step therapy is not neutralized by requiring faster paperwork. If the underlying optimization target is reduced utilization, the system will find new instruments when old ones are regulated. The specific policy changes; the logic regenerates.</p>
  <p>The inflammation does not pause for the exception process. The cartilage does not wait for the appeals deadline. At some point the question is not whether the system is reforming — it's whether an incentive structure this profitable is capable of it.</p>
</section>

